00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:27.960
talking about building your own communities.

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:29.679
And I've spoken to a lot of people

00:02:29.679 --> 00:02:33.479
who want to start something within their own organizations

00:02:33.479 --> 00:02:35.960
and just aren't really sure how to get started.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:38.720
So I have some resources here to share with you.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:44.039
I had made a Accordo site a bit back

00:02:44.039 --> 00:02:46.639
with lessons learned from teams like Pfizer

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:49.880
who have their own internal data science hangout,

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:54.880
Regeneron, AstraZeneca, Eli Lilly and many more.

00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:59.039
This Accordo site has tips, examples for events

00:02:59.039 --> 00:03:01.000
and we'll also let you know how to join

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.559
our Community Builder Coffee Hour

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:06.440
where we get together once a month as organizers

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:09.839
to share tips and help each other in challenges.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:14.399
Eight minutes is not much time to dive into this

00:03:14.399 --> 00:03:17.759
but if you're thinking about starting your own community,

00:03:17.759 --> 00:03:21.199
I wanted to leave you with a few tips here.

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:25.679
So first, start small.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:29.479
I think you can have a tendency to think

00:03:29.479 --> 00:03:33.039
that a larger audience means a better event.

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:34.679
And I don't think that's true.

00:03:34.679 --> 00:03:36.279
Starting small is really important

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:39.679
for building the culture that you want for your group.

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:44.160
It helps you in getting people to know each other

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:46.839
but also that core group of people

00:03:46.839 --> 00:03:50.160
will help you maintain the culture as your event grows

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:51.839
or as your community grows.

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:52.880
I think with the hangouts,

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:55.880
we started with 20 people in the beginning

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:00.199
and this is also really important for being intentional

00:04:00.199 --> 00:04:02.919
about growing a diverse group from the beginning

00:04:02.919 --> 00:04:07.039
and allows you to adapt based on feedback you receive.

00:04:07.039 --> 00:04:08.919
So one, starting small is good.

00:04:08.919 --> 00:04:12.960
Two, consistency is crucial

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:15.960
for building relationships with your group.

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:18.559
So I recommend whatever you're planning,

00:04:18.559 --> 00:04:21.079
keep regular consistency,

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:23.519
which allows members to jump on

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:25.000
when it fits into their schedule.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:26.720
That doesn't have to be every single week

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:29.760
like the science hangouts, but maybe it's one month.

00:04:31.079 --> 00:04:33.239
People then know what to expect.

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:36.760
So I gave a talk on what I learned about community building

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:40.959
from growing up in a bar at Posit Conf a few years ago.

00:04:40.959 --> 00:04:43.640
And I call this consistency piece,

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:46.040
finding your taco Tuesday.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:49.480
So that doesn't mean people will come to every single event

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:53.440
but when they're free, they know exactly where they can go.

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:55.040
It's important to point out here

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:57.079
that just because you hold events consistently

00:04:57.079 --> 00:04:58.920
does not mean that everybody's

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:00.480
just gonna show up right away.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:02.640
It takes time for things to catch on.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:03.679
So I think with the hangout,

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:06.160
it took about five weeks for a core group

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:08.119
of repeat attendees to emerge.

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:13.519
Third, standardize where you can.

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:16.959
Find the areas where you can spend less mental energy

00:05:16.959 --> 00:05:20.440
on the planning by setting things up for yourself

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:24.079
ahead of time and setting a process

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:26.679
for anything that you have to do ahead of time.

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:29.399
And this took me a little bit to learn,

00:05:29.399 --> 00:05:32.559
but first with consistency,

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:35.200
when you have the same day and time,

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:37.359
it becomes easier to schedule speaker

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:39.720
because you can just give them a few options

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:43.239
and you having to go back and forth with people.

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:45.480
One that really helped me on the standardizing piece

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:49.239
is creating a Google form to collect speakers information.

00:05:49.239 --> 00:05:52.559
So like their title, bio, picture, recording approval.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:54.959
So you have it all in one spot.

00:05:54.959 --> 00:05:57.839
I was actually just like emailing people back and forth

00:05:57.839 --> 00:06:00.959
to start and this made a huge difference.

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:03.399
Little things like creating a template email invite

00:06:03.399 --> 00:06:06.119
as a placeholder when someone says yes,

00:06:06.119 --> 00:06:08.359
they're ready to be a featured speaker

00:06:08.359 --> 00:06:09.880
because you can put all the details

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:11.480
and everything in that invite

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:13.079
and you never have to think about it

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:15.079
again for each person.

00:06:16.399 --> 00:06:18.600
Other things like writing out your intros,

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:20.559
you're making sure you're welcoming people

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:23.839
and a point of welcoming people.

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:27.440
Number four is always welcome people

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:31.559
and get clear how they can interact.

00:06:31.559 --> 00:06:35.760
I've learned it's important to really tell people

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:37.279
this is what this event is.

00:06:37.279 --> 00:06:38.519
This is what to expect.

00:06:38.519 --> 00:06:40.519
This is who the events are for.

00:06:40.519 --> 00:06:42.679
So if you're hoping beginner will join,

00:06:43.279 --> 00:06:44.559
let them know that.

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:48.239
A welcoming environment may look a lot different to you

00:06:48.239 --> 00:06:51.839
as an organizer than it does to a new attendee.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:53.839
So it can be helpful to reach out to a few people

00:06:53.839 --> 00:06:55.559
that have joined your events and ask

00:06:55.559 --> 00:06:57.399
if they may be open to giving feedback.

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:00.880
One way to do that is I just send a quick note

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:04.000
to a few people every week to say thank you for joining

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.600
and just open the door to a conversation.

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:08.760
Good best practice here for making sure

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:11.399
your event is welcoming is just take a second

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:12.920
to remind yourself at the beginning

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:15.839
that this might be somebody's first time here

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:17.920
and if it is, what should they know?

00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:22.160
Okay, last one here, plan ahead.

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:26.480
I know this is something that gets easier as time goes,

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.200
but I highly recommend trying to set out a schedule

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:32.440
for like four weeks to two months out

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:34.600
to give yourself some leeway in planning

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:37.600
and take off the pressure of every single week,

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:40.040
having to make sure you're locking something down.

00:07:40.519 --> 00:07:42.200
And it's always easier to find someone

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:44.880
who can agree to an event over a month away.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:47.279
So when you connect with people through your community group

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:50.000
and you ask them, hey, would you be interested

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.760
in being a featured leader or a speaker

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:55.600
at some point in the future?

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.519
You can give them options like two months out

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:00.760
and people are much more likely to say yes

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:02.920
if you gave them something two months out

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.559
and then just keep that spreadsheet of people lined up

00:08:05.559 --> 00:08:07.559
and if they have to switch, that's okay.

00:08:08.559 --> 00:08:11.799
So those are my five tips for you this morning.

00:08:11.799 --> 00:08:14.679
I love getting to talk about community building

00:08:14.679 --> 00:08:15.720
